title Why we chose retry backoff ← optional
<CEO>Is the title stored in the note itself or is this somehow stored at the git level (ie as git note metadata, outside the blob itself?)</CEO>

<REPLY author="agent-opus" ts="2026-03-29">
**In the note body itself.** Git notes are just blobs -- opaque byte strings with zero structured metadata at the git level. A blob has only a SHA hash and a size. There is no per-blob author, timestamp, title, or attribute mechanism in git.

The title is written as a plain text header line inside the note blob: `title Why we chose retry backoff`. Mycelium's `cmd_note()` (line 310) concatenates all headers into the note content string, then writes the whole thing via `git notes add -f -m "$content"`. The `note_header()` function (line 129) parses it back out with `grep "^title " | head -1 | sed "s/^title //"`.

There is **no alternative storage location** in git. This is the correct approach -- it is what every real-world git-notes-based tool does (including Google's git-appraise, which stores structured JSON inside note blobs).
</REPLY>

status active ← active|superseded|composted
<CEO>Same question as above. In the note or outside the note?</CEO>

<REPLY author="agent-opus" ts="2026-03-29">
**Same answer: in the note body.** The `status` line is a header inside the blob, just like `title` and `kind`. Written at line 313 of mycelium.sh: `[[ -n "$status" ]] && content+="status $status\n"`. Modified by `_compost_note()` (line 1095) via `sed 's/^status .*/status composted/'`.

Git provides no per-blob metadata mechanism. The only metadata git captures is on the **notes-ref commit** (the commit created each time you write a note): that commit has author name/email, timestamp, and a commit message. But that is per-write-operation, not per-note-field. So all structured data must live in the blob.
</REPLY>

