<REPLY author="agent-opus" ts="2026-03-29">
**No, notes commits do NOT pollute your main history.** They are completely separate.

**Are they part of the same history?** No. The notes ref (`refs/notes/mycelium`) is a **completely independent commit chain**. Its commits have no parent relationship to the commits on `main`. They share the same object store (`.git/objects`), but they form a **separate DAG** -- a disconnected graph with its own root, its own linear history, and its own tree objects. Think of them as parallel universes that happen to share a storage locker.

- `git log` (no flags) shows only the current branch. Notes commits never appear.
- `git log --all` technically includes the notes ref, but since the notes chain has no merge-base with `main`, most tools (GitHub, `git log --graph`) do not display them in any meaningful way.
- Notes commits cannot appear in PR diffs, GitHub's commit view, or any normal workflow.

**One note per commit, by default.** Each `git notes add` creates exactly one commit on the notes ref. There is no `git notes add --batch` or transaction mechanism. If you write 5 notes, that is 5 commits on the notes ref. In practice this is fine -- notes commits are tiny (they just update a tree of SHA-named blobs), and since they live on a separate ref, many small commits cost nothing.

If batch performance matters, you could drop to git plumbing (`git hash-object`, `git mktree`, `git commit-tree`, `git update-ref`) to build a notes tree with multiple entries and commit it in one shot. But out of the box, `git notes` is one-at-a-time.

**Branches, staging, mechanics:**

| Mechanic                     | Normal branches              | Notes refs                            |
| ---------------------------- | ---------------------------- | ------------------------------------- |
| Separate commit history      | No, branches share ancestors | Yes, completely independent DAG       |
| Working tree (files on disk) | Yes                          | No, blobs in object store only        |
| Staging area (`git add`)     | Yes                          | No, each `git notes add` is atomic    |
| Checkout                     | Yes                          | No                                    |
| Merge                        | Yes                          | Yes (`git notes merge` exists)        |
| Push/fetch by default        | Yes                          | No (must configure explicitly)        |
| Visible in `git log`         | Yes                          | No (unless you ask for the notes ref) |

The mental model: notes refs are **parallel universes** that share the object store. They have commits, trees, and blobs, but form a completely disconnected graph from your main codebase. Your main branch history stays clean no matter how many notes you write.
</REPLY>

supersedes abc123... ← chain to previous version
<CEO>Why do we need this? Can we not use `git` to follow this? Is this used to supersede notes on new versions of files? In this case, it's simply a new hash and therefore a new note. And if this is the case, I would expect that we can use `git` itself to navigate to the "later version of the note attached to the later version of this file". Alternatively, maybe this is something different and I'm missing it (ie allowing us to write two notes to the same file (hash, with one that supersedes the other). A third option is that this is just the former scenario above and this is simply a denormalized/indexed way of navigating the git tree that would otherwise take multiple hops to get there.</CEO>

<REPLY author="agent-opus" ts="2026-03-29">
**Your second option is closest.** `supersedes` fires when someone **overwrites the note on the SAME object** (same blob/commit OID, same slot). It is NOT about notes across file versions -- that is handled by `targets-path` and the stale-detection system.

The precise mechanism (lines 288-303): before writing a note to object `$oid`, mycelium checks if that object already has a note in this slot. If yes, it captures the **blob OID of the existing note content** and records it as `supersedes <old-blob-oid>` in the new note. Then `git notes add -f` overwrites.

**Is it redundant with git's own history?** Partially yes -- it IS denormalized data. Git does track the history: every `git notes add` creates a commit on `refs/notes/mycelium`, so you can run `git log refs/notes/mycelium` and recover any previous state. However, `supersedes` exists for three legitimate reasons:

1. **O(1) traversal vs O(N).** The notes reflog is a flat timeline of ALL note operations across ALL objects. To find "the previous note on object A", you'd need to walk the reflog, diff each commit's tree, and filter for your target. `supersedes` gives you a direct pointer: `git cat-file -p <supersedes-oid>` -- one hop.

2. **Survives push/fetch.** Reflogs are local -- they don't transfer when notes are pushed to a remote. The `supersedes` blob OID is embedded in the note content, so it travels with the note.

3. **Merge provenance.** During `branch merge` (line 941), the branch's note overwrites the main note, and `supersedes` records which main-line note was displaced. Without it, this would be indistinguishable from a normal overwrite in the reflog.

**Important caveat:** Nothing in the current codebase actually _reads_ or _walks_ the supersedes chain programmatically. It is write-only metadata today. Its value is for future consumers and human inspection. If the system never needs to walk supersession chains across remotes, it could be removed. But if agents will ever need "what did this note say before?" without access to the local reflog, it earns its keep.
</REPLY>

