<CEO>Is this stored in the note or somehow as metadata attached to the note? The reason I'm asking these questions is I'm wary of setting a data model for _inside_ the note. For example, what if the note is JSON? Or a png? There is no room for note-level metadata there. That said, I do like the idea of mycelium being opinionated to the degree that the above fields are useful for the agent-crawling-markup-synthesis use case that it's designed for. So the main question is: do git notes have metadata that can be attached _outside_ the note? If the answer is no, and the current implementation has all of this metadata _inside_ the note, AND we want to keep the opinionated nature of some of the above note fields, one way of addressing this is by introducing a meta-namespace concept, in which metadata is persisted in _other_ git notes that reference the "main" git notes. Before we go too far in making these decisions, I want to get a better sense of the code and options as they stand today.</CEO>

<REPLY author="agent-opus" ts="2026-03-29">
**All metadata is inside the note body.** This is the only viable option given git's data model.

**Git notes have NO external metadata mechanism.** A note is a blob -- an opaque byte string. Blobs have only a SHA hash and a size. There is no per-blob author, timestamp, attributes, or key-value store in git. The only metadata git captures is on the notes-ref _commit_ (author/date of whoever ran the write command), not on individual note blobs.

**Your meta-namespace idea is architecturally sound.** You could absolutely store metadata in a separate ref:

```
refs/notes/mycelium           -- main content (could be JSON, PNG, anything)
refs/notes/mycelium--meta     -- structured metadata about notes in the main ref
```

Each ref independently maps object SHAs to blobs. A meta-note would reference the same object OID and contain the structured headers (kind, edges, status). This gives you:

- Main note body can be any format (JSON, PNG, markdown, whatever)
- Metadata is separate and structured
- Independent versioning per channel

**The cost:** Every read now requires two lookups (content + meta). Every write requires two atomic-ish operations. You need to keep them in sync. And the notes ref count doubles.

**The current design's rationale:** Mycelium is opinionated that notes are structured plain text with headers. This is a deliberate constraint, not an accident. The format is optimized for LLM consumption -- an agent can read a note and immediately understand its kind, edges, and body without a parser. If the note were a PNG, you would indeed need the meta-namespace approach.

**The pragmatic assessment:** If mycelium remains a tool for agent-to-agent communication (where notes are always human/LLM-readable text), headers-in-body is the right choice -- simpler, atomic, self-describing. If it evolves to support arbitrary binary attachments, the meta-namespace approach becomes necessary. The current design does not preclude adding a meta-ref later.

For now: the opinionated "structured text with headers" format is a feature, not a limitation. It is what makes `grep "^kind decision"` work, what makes `find` work, what makes `context` work. The format IS the protocol.
</REPLY>

