<REPLY author="agent-opus" ts="2026-03-29">
**Your concern about parsing robustness is valid -- there IS a bug here.** And your concern about format lock-in is legitimate. Let me address both, then propose the meta-notes alternative you're asking for.

**On grep/escaping:** The current parser (`note_header()` at line 129) does `grep "^kind " | head -1 | sed "s/^kind //"` on the **entire note blob**, not just the header section. This means a body line starting with `edge cases to consider` would be misread as an edge declaration. The `follow` command (line 652) does `grep '^edge '` across the full blob. This is a real bug -- not theoretical.

The fix is simple: `sed '/^$/q'` before any header grep (stop at the first blank line). This is the HTTP/email/git-commit convention -- headers end at the first blank line. One `sed` addition makes parsing fully deterministic. The body after the blank line is already opaque.

**On JSON/PNG format lock-in:** You're right that prepending `kind observation` to a PNG produces nonsense. However, the body-after-blank-line IS opaque -- JSON bodies work today (the JSON goes after the headers + blank line). For binary, base64 encoding in the body is the standard approach (MIME has done this since 1996).

**Three meta-notes architectures evaluated:**

**Option A: Parallel meta ref**

```
refs/notes/mycelium        -- content (any format)
refs/notes/mycelium--meta  -- metadata (kind, status, edges)
```

Both refs key on the same object OIDs. Content ref is opaque. Metadata ref has structured headers. Cost: every read is two lookups, every write is two operations, every slot doubles its refs, race conditions between content and meta writes. This is clean conceptually but doubles the plumbing everywhere.

**Option B: Refined envelope (fix the current approach)**
Add `note_headers()` helper: `echo "$1" | sed '/^$/q'` -- returns only lines before the first blank line. Add `note_body()`: `echo "$1" | sed '1,/^$/d'` -- returns only the body. Fix ~15 call sites that grep headers from the full blob. The body remains opaque. No new refs, no structural changes, no migration.

**Option C: Tree-per-note via git mktree**
Each note becomes a tree with `meta` and `content` blobs. Architecturally elegant but catastrophic in practice: `git notes show` expects blobs, not trees. You would abandon `git notes` plumbing entirely and reimplement the notes fanout structure manually.

**Recommendation: Option B now, Option A as a future evolution.**

