<CEO>Is there any way to capture author or timestamp in the git notes metadata? Or would it have to go in file itself? BTW: is there any sensible way to "version" git notes (ie updates to a note in the same namespace attached to the same hash?). I was sort of guessing not, but perhaps there is? If not, I suppose we could sort of back into a clunky versioning mechanism by using (abusing, lol) the namespace concept?</CEO>

<REPLY author="agent-opus" ts="2026-03-29">
**Author and timestamp ARE captured -- but on the notes-ref commit, not the blob.** Every `git notes add` creates a commit on `refs/notes/mycelium`. That commit records `user.name`, `user.email`, and the current timestamp. To retrieve who wrote a specific note:

```bash
# Find the commit that last touched the note for <object-sha>
OBJ=abc123def456...
FANOUT="${OBJ:0:2}/${OBJ:2}"
git log refs/notes/mycelium --diff-filter=AM -- "$FANOUT" --format='%an <%ae> %ai' -1
```

Since each `git notes add -f` call creates exactly one commit, there is a 1:1 mapping between note writes and commits. Author and timestamp are reliably recoverable per note write. Mycelium could surface this via `read` output without storing author/timestamp in the note body at all.

**Versioning: yes, git gives you this for free.** The notes ref is a normal git history. Every overwrite is a commit. You can see every version of a note:

```bash
git log -p refs/notes/mycelium -- "$FANOUT"
```

Each commit that changed the note shows up as a diff with author and date. This is why `supersedes` is denormalized data -- git already tracks the history natively.

**You do NOT need to abuse namespaces for versioning.** The notes-ref commit history IS the version history. `git log refs/notes/mycelium` shows every note write ever made. You can diff between any two points. You can recover any previous state. The reflog adds another layer (local only, doesn't push).

**The one caveat:** Reflogs are local -- they don't transfer on push/fetch. The commit history DOES transfer (it is the notes ref itself). So version history is available on any clone that has fetched the notes ref, not just locally.

**Summary table:**

| Question                   | Answer                                                        |
| -------------------------- | ------------------------------------------------------------- |
| Author/timestamp from git? | Yes -- from the notes-ref commit, recoverable per write       |
| Versioning of one note?    | Yes -- `git log -p refs/notes/X -- <path>` shows full history |
| Need namespace abuse?      | No -- commit history gives you this natively                  |
| Does version history push? | Yes -- the notes ref commit chain transfers on push/fetch     |
| Per-blob metadata?         | No -- blobs have only SHA and size, nothing else              |

</REPLY>

