<REPLY author="agent-opus" ts="2026-03-29">
**Three format options were researched, drawing on git-appraise (Google), W3C Web Annotations, mdcomments, and Hypothesis fuzzy anchoring.**

### Option A: Multi-Note JSON (Recommended)

Parent note stays in `refs/notes/mycelium` as-is. Comments go to a parallel ref (`refs/notes/mycelium--discuss` or `--slot discuss`), attached to the same object. Each comment is one JSON line, appended via `git notes append`:

```
{"id":"a1b2c3","ts":1711670400,"author":"ceo","anchor":{"quote":"The slot system provides namespace isolation","prefix":"...","suffix":"..."},"body":"Do we need slots at all?"}
{"id":"d4e5f6","ts":1711670500,"author":"agent-opus","parent":"a1b2c3","body":"Slots map 1:1 to refs already. The abstraction adds naming conventions."}
{"id":"g7h8i9","ts":1711670600,"author":"ceo","parent":"d4e5f6","body":"Keep them but document as optional sugar."}
```

A "weaving" renderer merges parent + comments into a unified view, inserting threaded comments at their anchor points. **Concurrent-safe** by design: each comment is one appended line, `git notes merge -s cat_sort_uniq` handles conflicts automatically. This is exactly what Google's git-appraise used at scale for code review.

**Content anchoring** uses a TextQuoteSelector pattern (quoted text + prefix + suffix context). This survives edits to surrounding content, unlike line numbers which break immediately.

### Option B: Inline Tags (What REVIEW.md Already Does)

Everything in one note blob. Comments use `<CEO>`, `<REPLY>` tags inline. This is exactly what this document is doing right now.

**Pros:** Human-readable without tooling, agents see full decision history in context.
**Cons:** No viable merge strategy for concurrent writers, blob grows without bound.

### Option C: Hybrid (Inline Anchors + Sidecar Discussion)

Parent note has lightweight `[^c-id]` markers. Sidecar ref has the full threaded comments targeting those anchors.

**Pros:** Parent note stays clean, anchors are precise.
**Cons:** Most complex to implement, requires editing the parent note to add markers.

### Recommendation

**Option A is the right foundation** for structured, multi-participant, async discussion in git notes. It is concurrent-safe, append-only (aligns with mycelium's philosophy), proven at scale (git-appraise), and the parent note stays immutable.

**Option B (what this document uses) is the right degenerate case** for quick, informal discussion. Nothing stops someone from writing comments directly into a note body. But for systematic threaded commentary across agents and humans, the sidecar JSON approach scales.

**Implementation path:** New slot `discuss`. New commands: `mycelium comment <target> --author <name> -m "text" [--reply-to <id>] [--anchor "quoted text"]` and `mycelium discuss <target>` (renders woven view). Backward compatible -- existing notes are untouched.

This is a powerful direction and directly aligns with the vision of this document becoming a git note with threaded discussion attached.
